description:
In this sixth volume of the worlds greatest science adventure magazine its up to Atomic Robo and the Tesladyne Action Scientists to rescue a group of 5 astronauts trapped in an orbiter that has lost all power. With only seven hours to plan and execute the daring rescue the team jumps into action, pulling all Tesladyne personnel off of non-essential projects. Consequently, when the call comes in about an entire historic building gone missing in Bletchley Park, England Robo is forced to delegate the investigation to doctors Martin and Louis...pulling them off of polar bear patrol in Norway and sending them to investigate the disappearance. Their only clue, a note stating "The invisible house is the ghost of Station-x."

deck: A Japanese manga series created by Akihito Yoshitomi in 1996.
description:
Eat-Man is a Japanese manga series that was created by Akihito Yoshitomi in 1996. It was serialized by MediaWorks, a Japanese publishing company, in their manga magazine Dengeki Comic Gaointo until 2002, resulting in a total of 19 volumes. Only about the first two of these volumes however were released in English by Viz.

The series follows the adventures of Bolt Crank, an explorer (a form of mercenary) who has the ability to eat virtually anything and then reform it from his body. Despite being willing to work for whoever can pay, Bolt still manages to abide by a set standard of morals and ethics.

Most of Bolt's adventures end up being a series of one-shots, but certain stories carry over to later ones, with certain characters and plot points reappearing.

The world of Eat-Man itself is a mixture of Cyberpunk sci-fi and fairy tale fantasy, with many of Bolt's adventures taking place in entirely separate times and even worlds.
name: Eat-Man

description:
Batman and Robin (Volume 2)

For Pre Flashpoint volume 1, refer to Batman and Robin.

Written by: Peter J. Tomasi (#1 - Present)

Drawn by: Patrick Gleason (#1 - 8; 10 - Present); Lee Garbett (#9)

A "New 52" volume of Batman and Robin (Vol 2) featuring Bruce and Damian Wayne as the father/son Dynamic Duo, written by Peter Tomasi, and drawn by Patrick Gleason.

Following Damian Wayne's death in the pages of Batman, Incorporated, for five months (#19-23) the title had a rotating cast of supporting characters, changing the volume's name for each issue with a slightly modified indicia of the unique title followed by the original title with issue number in brackets.

  • Batman and Red Robin #19
  • Batman and Red Hood #20
  • Batman and Batgirl #21
  • Batman and Catwoman #22
  • Batman and Nightwing #23

Villains Month Issues

In September 2013 DC's books focused on the villains after the events of Trinity War and Forever Evil. The issues were then numbered with .1, .2, .3, & .4.

  • Batman and Robin #23.1 - Two-Face #1 (Written by Peter J. Tomasi and drawn by Guillem March)
  • Batman and Robin #23.2 - The Court of the Owls #1 (Written by James Tynion IV and drawn by Jorge Lucas)
  • Batman and Robin #23.3 - Ra's Al Ghul and the League of Assasins #1 (Written by James Tynion IV and drawn by Jorge Lucas)
  • Batman and Robin #23.4 - Killer Croc #1 (Written by Tim Seeley and drawn by Francis Portela)

After September's Villains Month issues, the title continued with the rotating title with various supporting cast and members of Batman's rogues gallery until issue #33 when it resumed the original Batman and Robin title.

  • Batman and Two-Face #24-28 (The Big Burn story arc.)
  • Batman and Aquaman #29
  • Batman and Wonder Woman #30
  • Batman and Frankenstein #31
  • Batman and Ra's al Ghul #32

Collected Editions

  • Vol. 1: Born to Kill (#1-8)
  • Vol. 2: Pearl (#9-14, #0)
  • Batman: Night Of The Owls (#9)
  • The Joker: Death of the Family (#15-17)
  • Vol. 3: Death of the Family (#15-17)
  • Vol. 4: Requiem For Damian (#18-23)
  • DC Comics The New 52 Villains Omnibus (#23.1-23.4)
  • Batman Arkham: Two-Face (#23.1)
  • Vol. 5: The Big Burn (#24-28)
  • Vol. 6: The Hunt For Robin (#29-34, Robin Rises: Omega)
  • Vol. 7: Robin Rises (#35-40)
